@page "/accordions"

<PageTitle>Accordions</PageTitle>

<Container Class="py-4">
    <Row>
        <Column>
            <Div Class="text-center" Margin="Margin.Is5.FromEnd">
                <H1 Class="display-4 fw-bold text-primary">Accordions</H1>
                <Paragraph Class="lead text-muted">Collapsible content panels for presenting information in a limited space.</Paragraph>
            </Div>
        </Column>
    </Row>

    <Row Gap="Gap.Is4">
        <Column>

    <Section>
        <H2>Basic Accordion</H2>
        <Paragraph>Default accordion with single item expansion.</Paragraph>
        
        <Accordion Class="d-inline-block">
            <AccordionItem Name="item1">
                <AccordionHeader FullWidth="false">
                    <Strong>Accordion Item #1</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is the first item's accordion body. It is shown by default, until the collapse plugin adds the appropriate classes that we use to style each element. These classes control the overall appearance, as well as the showing and hiding via CSS transitions.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="item2">
                <AccordionHeader FullWidth="false">
                    <Strong>Accordion Item #2</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is the second item's accordion body. It is hidden by default, until the collapse plugin adds the appropriate classes that we use to style each element. These classes control the overall appearance, as well as the showing and hiding via CSS transitions.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="item3">
                <AccordionHeader FullWidth="false">
                    <Strong>Accordion Item #3</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is the third item's accordion body. It is hidden by default, until the collapse plugin adds the appropriate classes that we use to style each element. These classes control the overall appearance, as well as the showing and hiding via CSS transitions.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
        </Accordion>
    </Section>

    <Section>
        <H2>Multiple Items Expanded</H2>
        <Paragraph>Accordion that allows multiple items to be expanded at the same time.</Paragraph>
        
        <Accordion AllowMultiple="true">
            <AccordionItem Name="multi1">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Multi-Item #1</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This accordion allows multiple items to be expanded simultaneously. You can expand this item and others at the same time.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="multi2">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Multi-Item #2</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is the second item in the multi-expand accordion. Notice how you can have both this and the first item expanded at the same time.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="multi3">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Multi-Item #3</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is the third item. All three items can be expanded simultaneously in this accordion.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
        </Accordion>
    </Section>

    <Section>
        <H2>Flush Accordion</H2>
        <Paragraph>Accordion with flush styling (no borders or background).</Paragraph>
        
        <Accordion Flush="true">
            <AccordionItem Name="flush1">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Flush Item #1</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is a flush accordion item. It has no borders or background styling, giving it a cleaner appearance.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="flush2">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Flush Item #2</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        Another flush accordion item. The flush styling removes the visual separation between items.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="flush3">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Flush Item #3</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        The third flush item. Notice how the items flow together without visual breaks.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
        </Accordion>
    </Section>

    <Section>
        <H2>Accordion with Icons</H2>
        <Paragraph>Accordion items with custom icons in the headers.</Paragraph>
        
        <Accordion>
            <AccordionItem Name="icon1">
                <AccordionHeader IconName="info-circle">
                    <Strong>Information</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This accordion item has an information icon in the header. Icons can help users quickly identify the content type.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="icon2">
                <AccordionHeader IconName="warning">
                    <Strong>Warning</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This item has a warning icon. Different icons can be used to categorize different types of content.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="icon3">
                <AccordionHeader IconName="check-circle">
                    <Strong>Success</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This item has a success icon. Icons make the accordion more visually appealing and informative.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
        </Accordion>
    </Section>

    <Section>
        <H2>Disabled Accordion Item</H2>
        <Paragraph>Accordion with a disabled item that cannot be expanded.</Paragraph>
        
        <Accordion>
            <AccordionItem Name="enabled1">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Enabled Item</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is an enabled accordion item that can be expanded and collapsed normally.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="disabled1" Disabled="true">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Disabled Item</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This accordion item is disabled and cannot be expanded. The header will appear grayed out and non-interactive.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
            
            <AccordionItem Name="enabled2">
                <AccordionHeader>
                    <Strong>Another Enabled Item</Strong>
                </AccordionHeader>
                <AccordionBody>
                    <Paragraph>
                        This is another enabled item that works normally, even when other items are disabled.
                    </Paragraph>
                </AccordionBody>
            </AccordionItem>
        </Accordion>
    </Section>
        </Column>
    </Row>
</Container>
